http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/13i-0&fd=R&url=http://www.dailystar.com.lb/article.asp%3Fedition_id%3D1%26categ_id%3D3%26article_id%3D82576&cid=1116516999&ei=m-xeRsngAYf40QHv7IzQDQ The Daily Star - Business Articles - Nahr al-Bared clashes strangle business both inside and outside camp Send to a friend Save to My Web Nahr al-Bared clashes strangle business both inside and outside camp Traders lament costly security crisis Tuesday, May 29, 2007 TRIPOLI/BEIRUT: Before the clashes between the Lebanese Army and Fatah al-Islam began on May 20, Nahr al-Bared boasted the most viable economy of the 12 Palestinian camps and by all accounts was one of the North's main commercial hubs. After emerging unscathed from the 1975-1990 Civil War, Lebanon's second most populated camp became a thriving entrepot thanks to its location on the coast midway between Tripoli and Akkar. Palestinian merchants purchased wholesale goods in bulk from Tripoli and sold them tax-free inside the camp, boosting the economic fortunes of Nahr al-Bared residents and retailers in the country's second largest city. "People in Nahr al-Bared were pretty well off. Traders from the camp came to Tripoli to buy goods and sell them in Nahr al-Bared, and there was a lot of trade with the surrounding areas until Fatah al-Islam came and the army surrounded the camp," the head of Hamas in North Lebanon, Abu Rabih al-Chehabi, told Nahr al-Bared was off the radar of most media outlets before Fatah al-Islam moved into the camp, but based on the accounts of residents displaced to Beddawi, everything from ceramic tiles, toilet bowls, and electronics to clothing, food, and cigarettes were sold at low prices on the bustling commercial strip. Though the majority of residents were relatively poor, said Suhail Natour, director of the Human Development Center,a Palestinian NGO, commerce had thrived in Nahr al-Bared for decades. "Nahr al-Bared was the only camp not damaged during the Civil War, so it was a converging point for the interests of wealthy traders in Tripoli and Palestinian merchants," he explained. "Since it had a small port on shore, it became a smuggling point for Syrian goods to Lebanon since the Civil War and remained so [until recently]." Natour said there has been a tacit agreement among the Lebanese, Palestinian, and Syrian authorities to maintain the status quo, allowing cheap Syrian goods to be smuggled into the camp by sea and sold duty-free, fueling Palestinian - and to a lesser extent Syrian and Lebanese - investment in Nahr al-Bared's economy. Commerce inside Nahr al-Bared dipped briefly when a highway between Akkar and Tripoli was constructed along the eastern border of the camp, but quickly rebounded when soe of the affected merchants moved closer to the highway. It was not until the army set up checkpoints around Nahr al-Bared three months ago and began restricting entry that the market began to suffer. "People from Akkar came to buy clothes, food, everything because it was cheaper in Nahr al-Bared, because there were no taxes. But then the army put up all these checkpoints, and it started taking a long time to get in and out of camp, so people stopped coming," displaced camp resident Fadi Moussa said. "No one wanted to spend an hour waiting to get inside." Most Tripoli merchants interviewed by The Daily Star all reported a fall in business when the army began to monitor Nahr al-Bared, and all said sales have plummeted since the fighting began. Qassem Mokheiber, the manager of the Tripoli Plaza clothing store, said that the Nahr al-Bared traders' bulk purchases were one of the store's main sources of revenue. "We were naturally affected when the army arrived," he told The Daily Star. "Tripoli was the main source for wholesale traders from Nahr al-Bared. They bought everything from us - clothes, toys, food," Mokheiber added. "We've had a few Palestinians displaced to Beddawi come in and buy clothes since the fighting started, but the business is meager compared to what we used to have. We're barely breaking even." Sales have dropped to just 10 percent of regular levels since the fighting between the Lebanese Army and Fatah al-Islam began more than a week ago, he estimated. Though the extent of infrastructure damage is still unclear, Natour doubts that any investors with capital will rush to rebuild Nahr al-Bared's economy in the absence of a sustained cease-fire. The Daily Star encountered a butcher and a barber who had already established temporary locations in Beddawi just two days after they fled Nahr al-Bared. "The fighting has totally demolished the camp's economy. Apparently the motive is security, but practically it has influenced the economic nerve center of Nahr al-Bared," said Natour. "Beddawi will be a temporary replacement, but not long term because smuggling was done through the sea." Tags: Army, Business, Civil War, Fight, Lebanese, Lebanon, North, Palestinian, Syria, Syrian, Trade, Trip, War Send to a friend Save to My Web Your feedback is important to us! We invite all our readers to share with us their views and comments about this article. Click here NOW to Comment on this Article regulator predicts cellular sell-off will double penetration rate Beirut's retail and services sectors brace for another slow summer Habtoor Land theme park reopens for business after eight months Head of ratings agency says Lebanon's insurance sector is overcrowded Lebanese imports of industrial machinery jump 31.8 percent in first quarter Lebanon sees drop in sales of high-end property Lebanon predicts reduction in deficit to 35.17 percent Banks see Beirut's $400 million Eurobond sell-off as a done deal Tourism sector prays for quick resolution of latest crisis Shuaa Capital unveils plan to open new office in Beirut Lebanese government assures IMF that reforms are on track Business and labor team up to call for political truce More Books about Lebanon War , The Daily Star. All rights reserved. to contact our syndica