http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/18-1&fd=R&url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/05/31/AR2007053100995.html&cid=1116825594&ei=m-xeRsngAYf40QHv7IzQDQ Wife of Calif. Businessman Says Iran Is Holding Her Husband - washingtonpost.com Find Bars & Clubs View a Sample and Sign Up Today's Headlines & Columnists Daily Politics News & Analysis Do Religious Girls Have More Sex? House Majority Leader Tom DeLay Indicted Wife of Calif. Businessman Says Iran Is Holding Her Husband Washington Post Staff Writer Thursday, May 31, 2007; 10:48 AM The wife of California businessman Ali Shakeri today appealed to the Iranian government for information on her husband, who has been missing since May 8, according to family members in Iran. Shakeri, a peace activist, is the fourth American citizen reported detained by Iran in recent weeks. The Iranian government has denied holding him. In Today's A Section More in Today's Print Edition Save & Share Article Zohreh Shakeri said her husband called her three times from Tehran's notorious Evin Prison and asked her not to comment publicly on his situation. A family member in Tehran saw her husband at the prison two weeks ago and also was asked not to say anything publicly. But after 24 days of silence, Shakeri said she had decided to break her silence. "I need to know where my husband is. I'm devastated. I don't know what to do," she said in an interview today. She said she has not received a call from him since May 17. It is common for Iran to tell detainees to urge family members not to say anything about their detention, according to human rights groups. Shakeri, who graduated from the University of Texas in the 1970s, had returned to Iran to visit his mother, who was ill and died while he was there, his wife said. He was due to return on a flight May 8 but has not been seen since he went to the airport, according to friends and family. The activist group Human Rights Watch put out the first alert about him. Shakeri's appeal comes as a coalition of international human rights activists today called on Iran to immediately release two detained Iranian-Americans, clarify the status of Shakeri and lift the travel ban on a journalist who is a dual national. The coalition includes Amnesty International, Human Rights Watch, the International Federation for Human Rights, Reporters without Borders and Nobel laureate Shirin Ebadi, an Iranian human rights lawyer. "These measures appear to be an attempt by Iran's security authorities to sow fear into the wider community of journalists, writers, scholars and activists," they said in a joint statement. "Their exchanges with counterparts in other parts of the world underscore both their commitment to enhance mutual respect and recognition of human dignity through dialogue and to see human rights norms upheld in their country." Shakeri, a resident of Irvine, CA, may be the victim of an "enforced disappearance," the statement staid. Also jailed in Iran are American scholar Haleh Esfandiari and social scientist Kian Tajbakhsh. The Iranian government also has refused to allow Parnaz Azima, correspondent for U.S.-funded Radio Farda, to leave the country since January. All three were charged Tuesday with espionage and endangering Iran's national security. ACLU: Boeing Offshoot Helped CIA Boeing Unit Sued Over CIA Flights: ACLU: Firm Flew Terrorist Suspects Antiwar to the Corps: Marine Reservist-Protesters Face Discipline Home-Price Growth Slow in First Quarter Arkansas Court Ends School-Funding Suit Related Topics & Web Content Top 35 Most Viewed Comments that include profanity or personal attacks or other inappropriate comments or material will be removed from the site. Additionally, entries that are unsigned or contain "signatures" by someone other than the actual author will be removed. Finally, we will take steps to block users who violate any of our posting standards, terms of use or privacy policies or any other policies governing this si