http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/5-0&fd=R&url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/world/thaksin-tells-supporters-to-accept-party-ban/2007/05/31/1180205431418.html&cid=1116362226&ei=m-xeRsngAYf40QHv7IzQDQ Thaksin tells supporters to accept party ban - World - smh.com.au Welcome to The Sydney Morning Herald. Thaksin tells supporters to accept party ban BANGKOK: A constitutional court has banned the political party of the former prime minister Thaksin Shinawatra after finding it guilty of election fraud, in a ruling that could throw Thai politics into disarray. But Mr Thaksin on Wednesday urged his stunned supporters to accept the ruling. In a statement read by his lawyer in Bangkok, he also urged the generals who ousted him in a bloodless coup last September to speed up elections promised for December. "As founder who led the party until the coup, I must apologise to party members, the executive committee and every supporter for an unexpected outcome," Thaksin said. "I would urge everyone to stay calm and don't make any moves." The court barred Mr Thaksin and 110 other executives of the party from participating in politics for five years, removing from the scene some of Thailand's most powerful politicians. The prospect of Mr Thaksin's return to power and the resurgence of his party has been one of the chief concerns of the country's military leaders. The court ruled that the party, Thai Rak Thai, was guilty of paying small parties to stand against it in an election in April last year to satisfy a requirement for minimum participation. "It used parliamentary elections only as a means to achieve totalitarian power," Judge Vichai Chuenchompoonuj said. "It goes to show that the defendant does not believe in the democratic system. It also shows no respect for the rule of law, which is key to the democratic system." The nine-member court accused Mr Thaksin of using the party for his own gain and said the party had no ideology beyond its leader's ambitions. The rival Democrat Party, Thailand's oldest, was found not guilty of breaking the laws. Security was tight in Bangkok as the verdicts were read, but tension was much less than security officials had predicted. The announcement was greeted with cries and tears at Thai Rak Thai headquarters. Party leaders have said that if Thai Rak Thai was disbanded, they would come together in a new party. But a ban on participation of many of their executives was a serious blow to that plan. New York Times, Reuters send photos, videos & tip-offs to 0424 SMS SMH (+61 424 767 764), or us. on home delivery of the Herald - subscribe today Thaksin tells supporters to accept party ban Place a classified ad Copyright &#169; 2007. The Sydney Morning Herald. Browse for a Date Litvinenko 'was a British spy' Artificially bred China panda dies in the wild Australian envoy says sorry Actress shot herself: Spector defence Australia, Philippines sign security pact Saudi prisoner 'commits suicide' at Guantanamo Rights group sues Boeing unit over CIA abductions Iemma won't apologise to Jakarta Governor Bush faces Zoellick challenge Five US soldiers killed in Chinook helicopter attack Home affordability is the worst in 20 years; should we give up on owning a home? Do the ends justify the means in reality show Rambo: The Senior Years Our resident artist imagines Sly Stallone in a retirement village. Lawson cedes his place in the Domain to a Maori bouncer. Lucky, not so peaceful If you're looking for peace, go to Norway or New Zealand. Everest feels climate pinch Split image shows global warming in action. Sam and the City Weapons of mass seduction: What turns you on? With no man in tow, who does the singer call? Only way to stop smoking? All Men Are Liars: Today is International No Tobacco Day. TODAY'S TOP 10 ARTICLES Everest showing effects of climate change Gears puts Google in the driver's seat Waitress set for stardom after Clooney gig Women in Saffron's life get most of his $25m 'We made no mistakes' Off-duty 