cises with the U.S. and abolish the National Security Law in these talks. For its part, the South proposed a joint conference between state-run think tanks from the two sides, bilateral defense ministers¡¯ talks, the gradual reopening of cross-border railways and the repatriation of South Korean prisoners of war and South Koreans abducted by the North. The North Koreans continued to stress ¡°nationhood¡± as they had on the first day of the ministerial meeting. Kwon said the two Koreas should tackle ¡°internal affairs¡± without the intervention of foreign forces, citing the Kaesong Industrial Complex and South Korean package tours to Mt. Kumkang as good examples of bilateral cooperation. The North Korean Workers¡¯ Party daily or Rodong Shinmun and the Chosun Shinbo, the mouthpiece of the pro-Pyongyang General Association of Korean Residents in Japan or Chongryon, also emphasized the phrase ¡°between the two Koreas¡± in reports Wednesday. Unification Minister Lee asked for cooperation and hard work from the North. He recounted a fable told by China's first historian Sima Qian¡¯s Shiji about a man who concentrated so hard that he could penetrate a rock with an arrow. Kwon replied the two sides are even capable of ¡°penetrating iron with water drops¡± if they work together. The negotiations continue until Thursday night, with the results announced in a joint press release.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/12-4&fd=R&url=http://www.boston.com/news/world/europe/articles/2007/05/31/putin_slams_russian_tv_for_shoddy_foreign_fare&cid=1116841518&ei=m-xeRsngAYf40QHv7IzQDQ Putin slams Russian TV for shoddy foreign fare - The Boston Globe Putin slams Russian TV for shoddy foreign fare MOSCOW -- President Vladimir Putin said yesterday that Russian television was polluting young people's minds with cheap imports and urged broadcasters to embrace wholesome home-grown entertainment instead. Putin slams Russian TV for shoddy foreign fare By Guy Faulconbridge, Reuters | MOSCOW -- President Vladimir Putin said yesterday that Russian television was polluting young people's minds with cheap imports and urged broadcasters to embrace wholesome home-grown entertainment instead. The criticism fits in with a drive by Putin, who has overseen a resurgence in Russia's confidence and power on the world stage, to promote patriotic values and Russian culture. Railing against the bosses of national television stations who were among the officials attending a Kremlin meeting on culture, Putin said: "They buy anything on the international market as long as it is cheap." "For more than 15 years our youth have been living under the mass cultural influence of ersatz foreign substitutes," RIA news agency quoted Putin as saying. "We must create the conditions so that the coming of age of the younger generation takes place in a wholesome atmosphere of home grown culture, so that young people are brought up with high artistic taste and standards of behavior ." Russian state or state-controlled television channels, which have the biggest audiences, carry a mixture of news, domestic crime serials, Soviet films, Hollywood blockbusters, and reality shows. Imported franchises on Russian television include "Who wants to be a Millionaire?", which originated in Britain, and the French-owned game show "Fort Boyard." Several soap operas are based on imported concepts adapted for the Russian audience. &copy; Copyright 2007 Globe Newspaper Company. All Globe stories since 2003 are now FREE E-mail to a friend The New York Times Company
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/0-2&fd=R&url=http://www.ctv.ca/servlet/ArticleNews/story/CTVNews/20070530/nato_copter_070531/20070531%3Fhub%3DCanada&cid=1116821733&ei=m-xeRsngAYf40QHv7IzQDQ CTV.ca | Military confirms Canadian soldier died in crash CTV News with Lloyd Robertson Soldiers exit a CH-47 Chinook helicopter during operations as seen in this image made available by the U.S. Army. Canadian Forces Brig.-Gen. Tim Grant, commander of Task Force Afghanistan, speaks to reporters from Kandahar on Thursday, May 31, 2007. Military confirms Canadian soldier died in crash Updated Thu. May. 31 2007 9:29 AM ET The military has released the name of a Canadian soldier killed in a helicopter crash Wednesday in Afghanistan that left a total of seven troops dead. Master Cpl. Darrell Jason Priede was a military imagery technician -- or combat cameraman -- from CFB Gagetown, said Brig.-Gen. Tim Grant during a news conference at Kandahar Airfield Thursday. "Our deepest sympathies go out to the family and friends of this wonderful young Canadian. In working to bring peace to this troubled country he has paid the ultimate price," Grant said. "However, we should all remember that Darrell was involved in a good thing, a good fight, and we should be proud of what he has done." Priede was a passenger in the U.S. CH-47 Chinook helicopter when it went down in Helmand province, one of the most volatile regions of the country. In addition to Priede, five American crew members of the helicopter were killed, along with a British military passenger. Troops have secured the wreckage of the helicopter and are investigating the cause of the crash. Purported Taliban spokesperson Qari Yousef Ahmadi said Taliban militants shot down the helicopter, but the claim has not been independently verified. Initial reports have suggested that the helicopter was hit by a rocket-propelled grenade, a U.S. official told The Canadian Press. Maj. John Thomas, a spokesman for NATO's International Security Assistance Force on Thursday, said "there will be a full investigation." "We will try to determine everything that happened and to fully investigate the site." The helicopter went down at about 9 p.m. local time Wednesday, NATO officials said. A rescue team arriving at the scene was then ambushed by insurgents and had to call in air support to ward off the attackers. One Afghan civilian was injured by gunfire. Grant declined to comment on the operation Priede was involved in because the campaign is still underway. He said fighting in Helmand province has been heavy in recent weeks, and troops are working to clear out opposition fighters so that refurbishment of the Kajaki hydroelectric dam, a major development project in the area of the crash, can go ahead. "They are certainly showing now, particularly in the Helmand River valley, that they are trying to make a last stand in this area," Grant said. "At the end of the day, though, they are not being successful. They are being pushed back, they are being defeated by the ISAF forces on the ground." In recent months, violence has centred around the Kajaki Dam area, with U.S. and British forces fighting insurgents targeting the project. CTV's Steve Chao, reporting from Kandahar, said the dam project is a centrepiece in redevelopment efforts in the country. "This is one major project that NATO is hoping will win the hearts and minds down here by providing some stable electricity," Chao told CTV Newsnet. The Chinook has two rotors and is mainly used for transport. It can fit about 40 soldiers in addition to a small crew. Eight U.S. personnel died last February when their Chinook crashed in the southern province of Zabul, but the incident was not the result of a militant attack. Another 10 U.S. soldiers died in a Chinook crash in May 2006, after an attempted nighttime landing. But a 2005 U.S. helicopter crash, which killed 16 Americans, is believed to have been caused by a rocket-propelled grenade fired by militants. In total, 56 Canadian military personnel have now been killed in Afghanistan. With files from The Associated Press Military confirms Canadian soldier died in crash Feds, province, police blamed in Ipperwash report Lawyers denied access to secret hearings Canada can do more to go green: Schwarzenegger Watchdog says businesses failing to protect info Economy more than doubling pace of last quarter T.O. neonatal unit shut after infection kills baby B.C. lottery board to hold emergency meeting Quick thinking saved N.L. fishermen: rescuer The latest news, photos and interactives from Canada's mission in Afghanistan. CTV's Steve Chao accompanies Canadian troops on a mission. Profiles of the Canadian casualties in Afghanistan since April 2002. Afghanistan: A timeline of Canadian involvement following the September 11, 2001 terrorist attacks in the U.S. CTV Newsnet: Steve Chao from the Kandahar base CTV Newsnet: Canadian Forces Brig.-Gen. Tim Grant DND funding came up short for funeral: parents Report on CIDA's role in Kandahar not true: minister New report urges overhaul of Afghan mission Taliban ambush coalition convoy in Afghanistan
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/3-0&fd=R&url=http://www.theaustralian.news.com.au/story/0,20867,21829502-2703,00.html&cid=1116817584&ei=m-xeRsngAYf40QHv7IzQDQ US bid to rescue British hostages | The World | The Australian The Australian &mdash; The World US bid to rescue British hostages US forces raided Shia militia strongholds in eastern Baghdad yesterday after mounting evidence emerged that an Iranian-backed group was behind the abduction of five Britons. According to Iraqi and British officials working on the case, the kidnapping of a British IT expert and four private security guards bore all the hallmarks of the Mahdi Army, the militant group headed by Moqtada al-Sadr. The Shia religious leader returned to Iraq last week and there have been fears he would order a new wave of attacks against US and British targets. The US military announced yesterday that two more American soldiers had been killed in Iraq, confirming that May had become the deadliest month for American forces since 2004. The soldiers were killed late on Wednesday when a roadside bomb hit their foot patrol and brought US casualties for the month to 116 - the most since November 2004, when marines fought a fierce battle to retake the city of Fallujah. April was bloody for the US-led coalition, with 104 deaths. Taken together, the two past months have been the deadliest since the war began. Also yesterday, a suicide bomber hit a police recruiting centre in Fallujah, killing up to 25 people and wounding 50, police said. In another blow, a Sunni police chief praised by US forces for clearing his city of insurgents was arrested following an investigation into alleged murder, corruption and crimes against the Iraqi people. Colonel Hamid Ibrahim al-Jazaa, his brother and 14 bodyguards were taken into custody Tuesday in the city of Hit, 140km west of Baghdad, according to a statement by the public affairs office of Multinational Corps-Iraq. The statement gave no details of the allegations. As the hunt for the five Britons continued, it has been revealed British SAS troopers hunting for al-Qa'ida in Iraq are being diverted to lead the search for the men. The SAS and the Special Boat Service, the Royal Marine equivalent of the army's elite regiment, have squadrons in Baghdad, although their main task has been to work alongside American special forces. The SAS and SBS have been engaged in covert missions against al-Qa'ida for four years, giving them experience of operating in the most hostile and complex environment. Military sources said the search would need to be done with the greatest sensitivity. The "kinetic option" used against al-Qa'ida targets - tracking and eliminating - was not going to be the best solution. US commanders have backed away from taking on Mahdi Army gunmen because of the Iraqi Government's desire to keep al-Sadr, the Islamic cleric who controls the militia force, in the political process. If his men have taken the Britons, the focus will be on negotiating the safe release of the hostages, not going in with guns blazing. The Britons - a consultant and his four armed bodyguards - were snatched late on Tuesday by a large group of gunmen in Iraqi police uniforms. In an interview with BBC radio, Iraqi Foreign Minister Hoshyar Zebari noted the raid had taken place near Sadr City, an al-Sadr stronghold. He said it was too soon to blame a specific group, but said the nature of the kidnapping clearly pointed to the involvement of one of the Shia militant groups. Meanwhile, an Iraqi court yesterday sentenced a former minister in absentia to seven years in prison for spiriting more than $US1 billion ($1.25 billion) out of the country during his brief tenure. Hazem al-Shaalan was accused along with scores of other officials of embezzling money earmarked for weapons. He denied the charges, which were first raised in 2005. Appeal to junta on Thai parties Star's new role: the candidate US bid to rescue British hostages Bans could send threatened