http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/13-4&fd=R&url=http://www.thestar.com/comment/article/219765&cid=1116516999&ei=m-xeRsngAYf40QHv7IzQDQ TheStar.com - comment - Creating a field day for militias, large and small Full Text Article Archive TheStar.com - comment - Creating a field day for militias, large and small Creating a field day for militias, large and small May 31, 2007 04:30 AM The crises in Iraq, Gaza, Lebanon and Afghanistan are the inevitable outcome of treating the symptoms rather than the disease. Gaza: Israeli bombing won't bring peace any more than previous military crackdowns. American-Israeli help to bolster President Mahmoud Abbas' security forces won't stop Hamas from acquiring more rockets to hurl at Israel. The Saudi-sponsored unity government between Fatah and Hamas won't end their internecine warfare. "The problem is Gaza itself," writes Fawaz Turki, author of The Disinherited: Journal of a Palestinian Exile , who lives in Washington. "Israel may have evacuated its miserable colonists and soldiers from Gaza but it continues to control its airspace, offshore maritime access and its borders, determining the flow of goods, produce and people ... "The cumulative impact of sustained economic hardship, coupled with living under the thumb of a foreign occupier can be devastating to an individual's psychological, even cognitive and social functioning ... "Communities made inert by repression, social immobility or economic deprivation, will build up an inescapable drive towards war, towards an assertion of identity at the cost of mutual destruction." The World Bank, too, recently criticized the Israeli stranglehold on Gaza and the West Bank, the latter cut up into "ever smaller and disconnected cantons." Neither the Palestinian civil war nor the breakdown of the months-long ceasefire with Israel should have come as a surprise. Lebanon: About 400,000 Palestinian refugees there remain marginalized â€“ denied citizenship and restricted to menial jobs. It is in one of their 12 camps that Beirut is battling Fatah al-Islam, which vows to "fight the Jews and take the holy war to the frontiers of Palestine." Rushing U.S. military supplies to Prime Minister Fouad Siniora may help him crush this militia, but it won't guarantee that others won't emerge. Fatah al-Islam may or may not be the creation of Syria. The more relevant point is that it is easy for anyone to start a militia in the midst of misery. The other point is that Lebanon is politically paralyzed between pro- and anti-Hezbollah elements. Attacking Fatah al-Islam is easy, disarming the Hezbollah is not, so strong it emerged from last year's Israeli invasion. Iraq and Afghanistan: The U.S. presence in both has been a boon to terrorists. The U.S. State Department says terrorism shot up 25 per cent last year â€“14,338 attacks that killed 20,498 people, most in Iraq and Afghanistan. The leader of Fatah al-Islam was an associate of Abu Musab al-Zarqawi, the notorious Al Qaeda terrorist who was killed in Iraq last summer. Other jihadis from Iraq may be operating well beyond Lebanon, as indicated by terrorist incidents in Morocco and Algeria. Jihadi tactics from Iraq are being copied in Afghanistan. Propping up prime ministers Nuri al-Maliki in Baghdad and Hamid Karzai in Kabul won't guarantee any more success than propping up Abbas and Siniora. They have been rendered ineffective by the Israeli and American policies of occupations and endless war, with criminal disregard for civilian casualties and human suffering. Enter the radicals â€“ and Iran. Bilateral U.S.-Iran talks, long overdue and at last underway, won't end the carnage in Iraq. Tehran has little incentive to help there while the U.S. â€“ backed by some Sunni Arab dictators â€“ continues its sabre-rattling over the Iranian nuclear program. "The failure to find political and institutional solutions in Palestine, Lebanon and Iraq, along with the American rivalry with Iran for regional influence, has stirred up all kinds of conflicts and created a field day for militias, large and small," says Prof. Jim Reilly, a University of Toronto expert on the Middle East. "They have let loose a host of furies" â€“ none easily contained. , the Star's editorial page editor emeritus, appears Thursday in World and Sunday in the A-section. Contact him at Conrad Black on trial Great home delivery subscription deals here! More in the news Burlington soldier killed when helicopter shot down 'Don't let my son die in vain' A brother's quest for the truth moved mountains Report lays Ipperwash blame Nephew arrested in east-end slaying Lugovoi says British killed Litvinenko Record number of climbers conquer Everest Spain sues to recover sunken treasure 25 killed by Iraqi suicide bomber MOST POPULAR ON THESTAR.COM Horoscopes for Thursday, May 31 Woman bounced from Montreal gay bar Stefani makes a clean getaway at the ACC Don Cherry takes his plaid to U.S. Crisp and buttery oatcakes Home of the million-dollar tuneup Ho Sang to receive the Gomez Award Woman bounced from Montreal gay bar Careers at the Star Pages of the Past Star Store & Photo Sales &copy; Copyright Toronto Star 1996-2007
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/15-1&fd=R&url=http://english.people.com.cn/200705/31/eng20070531_379797.html&cid=1116847097&ei=m-xeRsngAYf40QHv7IzQDQ People's Daily Online -- Egypt terms Quartet statement on Gaza violence as unbalanced China at a glance China in brief 2004 CPC & state organs Selected Works of Deng Xiaoping UPDATED: 22:08, May 31, 2007 Egypt terms Quartet statement on Gaza violence as unbalanced on Thursday termed a statement by the international Quartet on the current Gaza violence as " unbalanced", saying it is not helpful to quelling violence in the region. Alaa Hadidi, spokesman for the Egyptian Foreign Ministry, voiced the dissatisfaction over the Quartet's Wednesday statement in a speech to local diplomatic editors, the official MENA news agency reported. The Quartet statement was a tantamount to a green light to to launch more attacks against the Palestinians, Hadidi was quoted as saying. After a meeting in Berlin Wednesday, diplomats from the Quartet, which groups , the United Nations and the European Union, called for an immediate stop of violence in the Mideast region as fighting between Israel and Palestinian militants continued to flare up. Hadidi noted that the Quartet asked the Palestinians to hold their fire while urged Israel to avoid fall of civilians during military operations in the Palestinian lands. "How can Israel avoid death of civilians while using heavy weapons in bombing targets located in residential areas?" The unbalanced statement jeopardizes the credibility of the Quartet as a neutral side, warned the Egyptian official. Hadidi also rejected Quartet's call for unconditional release of Israeli soldier Gilad Shalit who was kidnapped by Palestinian militant groups in June last year. The Quartet remarks will not help Egyptian efforts aiming at clinching a deal to free Shalit in return for some Palestinian prisoners, said Hadidi, criticizing the international group for failing to condemn the recent Israeli "kidnapping" of Palestinian lawmakers. The Quartet statement also misinterpreted the Arab Peace Initiative reactivated by Arab leaders during their summit meeting in Riyadh in late March, which provides a complete vision of a comprehensive peace in the region that will not be realized unless Israel withdrew from all occupied Arab lands, Hadidi said. However, the Egyptian official welcomed Quartet's support for holding dialogue between Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Olmert and Palestinian President , expressing Cairo's support to Quartet's call for an Israeli halt to settlement construction. Comment on the story Copyright by People's Daily Online, all rights reserved
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/14-0&fd=R&url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/religion/Story/0,,2091812,00.html&cid=1116680910&ei=m-xeRsngAYf40QHv7IzQDQ Malaysia rejects bid for Christian convert to remove Islam ID tag | Special reports | Guardian Unlimited Skip to main content Comment is free blog Arts & entertainment blog Special report: religious affairs Archived articles on religious affairs Malaysia rejects bid for Christian convert to remove Islam ID tag Lecturers refuse to spy on Muslim students Feminist, socialist, devout Muslim: woman who has thrown Denmark into turmoil No 10 accused of condoning Islamophobia over e-petition Interview: Ed Husain, author of The Islamist Government may issue sharia bonds, says Balls Allah, queen and the country Manal Omar on her five piece Islamic swimsuit 'Tactics backfiring' as jails try to curb radical Islam Sarfraz Manzoor on Muslim comedy tour Allah Made Me Funny Kelly launches bid to win over Muslims and fight extremism Kelly outlines plans to isolate extremists Lloyds launches sharia business account Muslim school assistant loses veil appeal Letters: Veil ban in schools will be divisive Malaysia rejects bid for Christian convert to remove Islam ID tag Ian MacKinnon, south-east Asia correspondent Thursday May 31, 2007 The highest court in Malaysia yesterday rejected a Muslim-born woman's appeal to be recognised as a Christian, ending a six-year legal battle that will heighten concerns over discrimination of the country's religious minorities. Lina Joy, 42, had fought the decisions of Malaysia's lower courts in an effort to have the word "Islam" removed from her identity card, arguing that the constitution guaranteed her religious freedom. But the panel of three judges decided, in a majority verdict, that it had no power to intervene in cases of apostasy. These cases fall under the jurisdiction of Malaysia's Sharia courts, which run in tandem with the country's civil courts. However, it has never been made clear which branch of the court takes precedence. The Malaysian constitution guarantees freedom of worship, but ethnic Malays must be Muslim by law. "She cannot simply, at her own whim, enter or leave her religion," Judge Ahmad Fairuz said during yesterday's ruling. "She must follow rules." But Judge Richard Malanjum, the only non-Muslim on the panel, said it was "unreasonable" to ask Ms Joy to turn to the Sharia court as she could face criminal prosecution because abandoning Islam is punishable by a fine or jail. Critics of the verdict expressed dismay and said it failed to uphold the legal rights of Malaysians. Two-hundred Muslim protesters who gathered in a prayer vigil outside the court yesterday greeted the verdict with cries of "Allahu Akbar" (God is great). Islam is the official religion in Malaysia, where 60% of the country's 27 million people are ethnic Malay. The woman, born Azlina Jailani, started attending church in 1990 and was baptised eight years later. She was given permission to change her name, but "Islam" remained as her religion on her identity card. More articles by John Aglionby Malaysian prime minister's office Send it to a friend Join our dating site today Guardian Unlimited &copy; Guardian News and Media Limited 2007
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/7-2&fd=R&url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/world/0,1518,485847,00.html&cid=1116810000&ei=m-xeRsngAYf40QHv7IzQDQ G-8 Foreign Ministers Meeting: US and Russia Trade Barbs in Potsdam - International - SPIEGEL ONLINE - News G-8 Summit in Heiligendamm G-8 FOREIGN MINISTERS MEETING US and Russia Trade Barbs in Potsdam Far from being a show of unity by some of the world's richest nations, next week's G-8 summit could fast deteriorate into a slanging match between the US and Russia. That, at least, was what happened when the G-8 foreign ministers gathered in Germany on Wednesday. Russian Foreign Minister Sergey Lavrov and US Secretary of State Condoleezza Rice exchanged verbal blows at the G-8 press conference Wednesday. Clashes between Russia and the US soured a meeting of G-8 foreign ministers on Wednesday, just one week before the main summit kicks off in Heiligendamm on Germany's Baltic coast. At the press conference in Potsdam, the site of the historic conference between the victorious Allies at the end of World War II, Russia's foreign minister Sergey Lavrov struck out at US plans to erect a missile defense system in Eastern Europe. He also criticized US policy on Kosovo and Lebanon. Lavrov accused Washington of launching a new arms race, saying that the US rationale for the shield was thin and that Moscow was not placated by the reassurances it had received. "All they are saying is 'don't worry it's not aimed at you,'" he complained. US Secretary of State Condoleezza Rice retorted that her country had repeatedly explained its plan to Russia. And she said that she agreed with Russian President Vladimir Putin's assessment that Russia's own strategic defenses could easily overpower the US system. "I hope that nobody has to actually prove that Condi is right about that," was Lavrov's sardonic response. The US want to deploy a radar system in the Czech Republic, along with inceptor missiles in Poland, to defend against possible threats from rogue states. However, Moscow perceives the move as part of a steady encroachment on its former sphere of influence. In the latest development in the escalating dispute between the two sides, Russia tested a new multiple-warhead intercontinental ballistic missile on Tuesday. Putin said on Thursday that the test was in direct response to US steps that have upset the strategic balance. The two ministers also announced that US President George W. Bush and Putin will meet at the beginning of July for bilateral talks at the private home of Bush's father, George H.W. Bush, in Maine. But the missile defense shield is not the only point of discord between the two countries. They are also sparring over the future of Kosovo. Russia backs Serbia, which opposes a UN plan to offer independence to the Albanian-majority province. Western powers are in favor of the plan, proposed by the UN mediator Martti Ahtisaari. "We and several of my European colleagues here believe that the Ahtisaari report provides the right basis for resolving the issue," Rice told the news conference. But Lavrov was combative on this issue too: "Our positions are diametrically opposed and I don't see any chances of the positions moving any closer together," he told the news conference. The Russian top diplomat also sniped at recent US arms shipments to the Lebanese army, which is currently engaged in fighting militants in Palestinian refugee camps, accusing Washington of "interfering in Lebanese affairs." Sign up for Spiegel Online's daily newsletter and get the best of Der Spiegel's and Spiegel Online's international coverage in your In- Politicians in Germany -- the current G-8 president -- will be desperately hoping that the two sides don't choose next week's summit meeting as another forum for airing their disagreements. Chancellor Angela Merkel had hoped that the leaders of the world's industrialized leaders and Russia could reach a breakthrough on tackling climate change and poverty in Africa. However, there are already indications that the US could decide any meaningful decisions on moves to curb climate change. While the Europeans want to set strict benchmarks for emissions reductions, the US prefers increasing the use of alternative energy -- to reduce dependency on oil. Although the Potsdam meeting could hardly be deemed a great success, there were some noises of unity from within the G-8. In a joint statement the foreign ministers said that they regretted that Iran was expanding its uranium enrichment activities. And Afghanistan and Pakistan, invited by Germany to attend Wednesday's meeting, vowed to deepen cooperation between their governments "at all levels," including border management, the fight against terrorism and the issue of Afghan refugees in Pakistan. Blogs discussing this story RELATED SPIEGEL ONLINE LINKS German Environment Minister Takes on the US: 'Time for America to Take Responsibility' The New Ice Age: Talking With Russia -- or Not Oil, Pigs and War Memorials Our Coverage of the G-8 Summit in Germany &copy; SPIEGEL ONLINE 2007 Reproduction only allowed with the permission of SPIEGELnet GmbH The Age of the Dragon: China's Conquest of Africa German Environment Minister Takes on the US: 'Time for America to Take Responsibility' Chavez Attacks Last Opposition TV Station Sarkozy Will Not Block Accession Talks with Ankara The Fence Is Closed: Security Tightens as G- World Bank Chief Zoellick: Asparagus Harvest in Trouble: A Shortage of Polish Workers in Germany A Rising Star in Danish Politics: Muslim Politician Is Messenger of Change G-8 SUMMIT IN GERMANY Tension on the Baltic: 8 Summit in Heiligendamm 8, Bono Says 'It's Time to Be Tough' An Interactive Map of the Summit Site: World Leaders Fenced In Germans Prepare Massive Security Precautions THE CRISIS IN IRAQ: CHAOS AT HOME, REFUGEES ABROAD The Growing Iraqi Refugee Crisis: Trading Civil War for Small- Living and Dying in Baghdad: One Day in the World's Most Dangerous City