http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/12i-0&fd=R&url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/6708459.stm&cid=1116841518&ei=m-xeRsngAYf40QHv7IzQDQ BBC NEWS | Europe | Russia blames US in missile row The News in 2 minutes Your news when you want it Also in the news Thursday, 31 May 2007, 13:53 GMT 14:53 UK E-mail this to a friend Russia blames US in missile row Mr Putin said Russia's actions were not aggressive Russian President Vladimir Putin has said a recent ballistic missile test was in answer to US plans to create a defence shield in Central Europe. Mr Putin said it was a "response to maintain the strategic balance in the world", in what he called a "new round of the arms race". He added that Russia would continue to improve its resources. Russia tested a new intercontinental ballistic missile, which can be armed with up to 10 warheads, on Tuesday. These actions by Russia should not be feared, they are not aggressive Europe diary: Missile defence "Our American partners have left the ABM (Anti-Ballistic Missile) Treaty," Mr Putin told a press conference. "We have warned them then that we will come out with a response to maintain the strategic balance in the world." Mr Putin defended Russia's actions, insisting they were not the "initiators of this new round of the arms race". "(Our partners) are stuffing Eastern Europe with new weapons," he said. "A new base in Bulgaria, another in Romania, a site in Poland, radar in the Czech Republic. What are we supposed to do? We cannot just observe all this." He added: "These actions by Russia should not be feared, they are not aggressive, it's just an answer to rather tough and unjustified unilateral actions by partners." Washington wants to deploy interceptor rockets in Poland and a radar base in the Czech Republic to counter what it describes as a potential threat from "rogue states" such as Iran and North Korea. The US maintains its system is not directed at the Russians, but Moscow says its security is being threatened. Russia's test launch took place at the Plesetsk cosmodrome in northern Russia on 29 May. The missile, called RS-24, was designed to evade missile defence systems, the Russian defence ministry says. The test missile successfully struck its target 5,500km (3,400 miles) away on the far eastern Kamchatka peninsula, the Russian Strategic Missile Forces said. E-mail this to a friend Europe diary: Missile defence 31 May 07 | Europe Russia tests long-range missile 29 May 07 | Europe Putin steps up missiles warning 27 Apr 07 | Europe Russia's treaty threat irks Nato 26 Apr 07 | Europe Russia upgrades nuclear missiles 05 Dec 06 | Europe Putin unveils 'new super missile' 31 Jan 06 | Europe UK 'behind Litvinenko poisoning' Russia blames US in missile row Turkish MPs force reform showdown MOST POPULAR STORIES NOW Harry Potter theme park planned Washington diary: Seeking a visa EMI strikes a deal with YouTube Ethnic split stirs Ivory coast crisis Most popular now, in detail US actor will run for president Italy inmates seek death penalty US urges new greenhouse gas goals Washington diary: Seeking a visa Online and offline worlds merge Most popular now, in detail Should record number of Everest conquerors be celebrated? What do search engines know about us from our online habits? Bahamas or border - oddities of the US immigration system Back to top ^^ Privacy and cookies policy
